\begin_layout Standard
At each period, a proportion of the buildings of category k is rehabilitated:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{h,k}^{REHAB}=\underset{k'}{\sum}REHAB_{h,k,k'}/BUIL_{h,k}$
\end_inset

.
 This proportion may not be constant over time.
 For instance, it may increase as the energy price increases because this
 gives an incentive toward more energy efficiency renovation.
 This can be modeled by assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{h,k}^{REHAB}$
\end_inset

 is endogenous and depends on the user cost of the building.
 Variation in that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{h,k}^{REHAB}$
\end_inset

 may also be exogenous due to the imposition of stricter energy efficiency
 requirements embodied in 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{h,k}^{REHAB*}$
\end_inset

.
 Naturally, the proportion of the buildings that are renovated cannot exceed
 1.
 But it appears logical to assume that it has also a lower bound (
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{h,k}^{REHAB\_l}$
\end_inset

 ) to account for irreversibility phenomena: even if the energy price starts
 to go down, it is possible that households will not lower their investment
 in energy efficiency.
 These considerations lead to the following specification:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\tau_{h,k}^{REHAB} & = & \tau_{h,k}^{REHAB*}+\eta_{h,k}\frac{UC_{h,k}^{REHAB}}{UC_{h,k}}\nonumber \\
0\leqslant\tau_{h,k}^{REHAB\_l}\leqslant & \tau_{h,k}^{REHAB} & \leqslant\tau_{h,k}^{REHAB\_h}\leqslant1\label{eq:8}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $UC_{h,k}$
\end_inset

 is the user cost of buildings of type k and 
\begin_inset Formula $UC_{h,k}^{REHAB}$
\end_inset

 is the user cost of the investment in the renovation of building k.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As explained previously, the rehabilitation of a building of a given class
 k can be done to different higher classes.
 It would be logical to assume that the choice between the higher classes
 is endogenous and depends on the relative cost of each option of renovation.
 However, because of the lack of data, it is difficult to model and calibrate
 such arbitrage.
 Moreover, this choice may be strongly determined by technical renovation
 standards with a small influence of relative prices.
 Therefore, we assume that this choice is exogenous, that is the share of
 class k buildings rehabilitated to class k' (
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{k,k'}^{REHAB}$
\end_inset

 ) is exogenous: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
REHAB_{h,k,k'} & = & \varphi_{h,k,k'}^{REHAB}.\tau_{h,k}^{REHAB}BUIL_{h,k,t-1}\\
\nonumber \\
\sum_{k'}\varphi_{h,k,k'}^{REHAB} & = & 1
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:8"

\end_inset

), we assume that the proportion of the buildings of category k to be rehabilita
ted depends on the user cost of buildings.
 We assume that the latter corresponds to the annual cost of the investment
 which consists of two components: (1) the annual cost of the investment
 itself including eventual interests, (2) annual energy cost.
 This leads to the following relation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
UC_{h,k}^{REHAB} & = & UC_{h,k}^{K\_REHAB}+UC_{h,k}^{E\_REHAB}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
UC_{h,k}^{E\_REHAB} & = & \sum_{k'=k+1}^{K}\varphi_{h,k,k'}^{REHAB}.UC_{h,k'}^{E}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Regarding the decision of rehabilitating the house to a higher class, the
 above user cost is compared to the user cost of a building remaining in
 class k: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
UC_{h,k} & = & UC_{h,k}^{K}+UC_{h,k}^{E}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
UC_{h,k}^{K\_REHAB} & = & P_{h,k}^{REHAB\_\delta^{BUIL}}(R_{h,k}^{CASH\_REHAB}+\frac{R_{h,k}^{LOAN\_REHAB}R_{h,k,t-1}^{I\_REHAB}LD_{h,k}^{REHAB}}{1-(1+R_{h,k,t-1}^{BUIL\_REHAB})^{-LD_{h,k}^{REHAB}}})\\
R_{h,k}^{LOAN\_REHAB} & = & 1-R_{h,k}^{CASH\_REHAB}\\
LD_{h,k}^{REHAB} & \leqq & 1/\delta_{h,k}^{REHAB}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
UC_{h,k}^{K} & = & P_{h,k,k}^{REHAB}\delta_{h,k}^{BUIL}(R_{h,k}^{CASH}+\frac{R_{h,k}^{LOAN}R_{h,k,t-1}^{I\_BUIL}LD_{h,k}}{1-(1+R_{h,k,t-1}^{I\_BUIL})^{-LD_{h,k}}})\\
R_{h,k}^{LOAN} & = & 1-R_{h,k}^{CASH}\\
LD_{h,k} & \leqq & 1/\delta_{h,k}^{BUIL}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta_{h,k}^{REHAB}=\sum_{k'=k+1}^{K}\varphi_{h,k,k'}^{REHAB}\delta_{h,k'}^{BUIL}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
