\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This appendix derives the optimality program of the producer and the consumer
 assuming a generalized CES (GCES) production and utility function.
 We show that the GCES function can be approximated in the neighborhood
 of the optimal stationary state by a Cobb-Douglas function for which the
 technical coefficients vary with the relative prices.
 This result greatly facilitates the deduction of linear demands functions
 for input and goods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
B-1
\begin_inset space \quad{}
\end_inset

GCES production function and factors demand
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us define a GCES production function as a 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 inputs-production function with different elasticities of substitution
 between each pair of input.
 We still assume a constant elasticity of substitution between 2 inputs
 along the isoquant.
 Let us assume that technology may be represented by a continuous and twice
 differentiable function, linearly homogeneous, strictly increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $(Q'(x_{ht})>0)$
\end_inset

 and concave 
\begin_inset Formula $(Q''(x_{ht})<0)$
\end_inset

 reflecting the law of diminishing marginal returns: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{t}=Q(X_{ht})\label{eq: production function}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{ht}$
\end_inset

 is the quantity of input (or production factor) 
\begin_inset Formula $h=[1;H]$
\end_inset

 used to produce the quantity of production (or output) 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{t}$
\end_inset

 .
 For algebraic simplicity, we assume a technology with constant returns
 to scale (i.e.
 the production function 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: production function"

\end_inset

 is homogeneous of degree 1) and the absence of technical progress.
 We shall relax these constraints latter.
 Driven by maximizing profit behaviour, the producer chooses her demand
 for each input by minimizing her production cost 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Cost function"

\end_inset

 subject to the technical constraint
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: production function"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
C_{t}=\sum_{h=1}^{H}P_{ht}^{X}X_{ht}\label{eq: Cost function}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{ht}^{X}$
\end_inset

 is the price of input 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

.
 The Lagrangian to this problem is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L_{t}=C_{t}-\lambda(Q_{t}-Q_{t}(X_{ht})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The necessary first order conditions are 
\begin_inset Formula $L'(X_{ht})=0$
\end_inset

 for all h and 
\begin_inset Formula $L'(\lambda)=0$
\end_inset

.
 The second order conditions ensure that the optimum is a minimum is always
 verified because of the convexity of the cost function 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Cost function"

\end_inset

 and strict convexity of the isoquants formed by the production function
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Cost function"

\end_inset


