\begin_layout Plain Layout
According to the technological constraint 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: production function"

\end_inset

, the strict convexity of the isoquant 
\begin_inset Formula $(X_{ht}''(X_{ht})>0)$
\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $Q''(X_{ht})<2Q'(X_{ht})$
\end_inset

.
 This condition is always verified since by assumption the left-hand side
 is negative 
\begin_inset Formula $(Q''(x_{ht})<0)$
\end_inset

 while the right-hand side is positive 
\begin_inset Formula $(Q'(x_{ht})>0)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 .
 The well-known first order condition says that at the optimum, the ratio
 between marginal productivities of two inputs equals the one between their
 prices:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{Q'(X_{ht})}{Q'(X_{h't})}=\frac{P_{ht}^{X}}{P_{h't}^{X}}\label{eq:FOC}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The production function 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: production function"

\end_inset

 can be linearized with the following first-order Taylor expansion:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dot{Q_{t}}=\sum_{h=1}^{H}\frac{Q'(X_{ht}).X_{ht}}{Q(X_{ht})}\dot{X_{ht}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Euler’s Theorem states that a function which is homogeneous of degree 1
 can be express as the sum of its arguments weighted by their first partial
 derivatives: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q(X_{ht})=\sum_{h=1}^{H}Q'(X_{ht}).X_{ht}\label{eq:Rem of prod factors}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fact that in equilibrium, the remuneration of the production factors
 must be equal to the value of the production provides another useful relation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{h=1}^{H}P_{ht}^{X}X_{ht}=P_{t}^{Q}Q_{t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The combination of equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FOC"

\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Rem of prod factors"

\end_inset

 gives at the neighbourhood of the stationary state a linear specification
 of the production function:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
\dot{Q_{t}} & =\sum_{h=1}^{H}\varphi_{ht}\dot{X}_{ht}\Leftrightarrow q_{t}=\sum_{h=1}^{H}\varphi_{ht}x_{ht}\label{eq:Prod function bis}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{ht}$
\end_inset

 is the share (in value) of input 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 in the production sometimes called Leontief technical coefficient
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
 & \varphi_{ht}=\frac{P_{ht}^{X}X_{ht}}{P_{ht}^{Q}Q_{ht}}\label{eq:value share}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have just shown that at the neighbourhood of the optimum any linearly
 homogeneous, twice differentiable, strictly increasing and concave production
 function can be approximated by a Cobb-Douglas with technical coefficients
 that varies over time.
 Moreover these technical coefficients correspond to the input share into
 production.
 They are stable in the long run because the specification of Three-ME guarantie
s the stability of ratios between prices and of input to production ratios.
 Suppose further that the direct elasticity of substitution – in the sense
 of Hicks (1932) and Robinson (1933) – between inputs 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $h'$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{hh'}$
\end_inset

 is not necessarily the same between each couple of production factors.
 This elasticity measures the change in the ratio between two factors of
 production due to a change in their relative marginal productivity, i.e.
 in the marginal rate of substitution (in the slope of the iso-production
 curve): 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
-\eta_{hh'} & =\frac{\partial\ln(X_{ht}/X_{h't})}{\partial\ln(Q'(X_{ht})/Q'(X_{h't})}\Leftrightarrow\partial\ln(X_{ht}/X_{h't})=\eta_{hh'}\partial\ln(Q'(X_{ht})/Q'(X_{h't}))\label{eq:direct elasticity of subst}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Integrating 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:direct elasticity of subst"

\end_inset

 with respect to time and then combining it with the optimality condition
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FOC"

\end_inset

 gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

