\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
 & \frac{X_{ht}}{X_{h't}}=\xi_{hh'}\Bigg(\frac{P_{ht}^{X}}{P_{h't}^{X}}\Bigg)^{-\eta_{hh'}}\label{eq:input share}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{hh'}$
\end_inset

 is the constant of integration which we calibrate to one for algebraic
 simplicity.
 Rewriting 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:input share"

\end_inset

 in terms of input share, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{ht}/\varphi_{h't}=\xi_{hh'}(P_{ht}^{X}/P_{h't}^{X})^{1-\eta_{hh'}}$
\end_inset

 , gives the well-known result that the inputs share is constant over time
 only in case of unit elasticity of substitution between all factors of
 production (Cobb-Douglas technology).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first order conditions
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:input share"

\end_inset

 and the production function 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Prod function bis"

\end_inset

 constitute a system of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 linearly independent equations and 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 unknowns.
 Its resolution give the demand for each factor as a positive function of
 output and negative function of relative prices between production factors:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
x_{ht}=\sum_{h=1,h\neq h'}^{H}\eta_{hh'}\varphi_{h't}(p_{ht}^{X}-p_{h't}^{X})\label{eq:demand of factors}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The introduction of technical progress and non constant return-to-scale
 is straightforward and does not alter the results.
 In the first case one can simply define 
\begin_inset Formula $X{}_{ht}=I_{ht}^{nput}P_{ht}^{rog}$
\end_inset

 as the efficient input, which includes the technical progress 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{ht}^{rog}$
\end_inset

 ,
\begin_inset Formula $I_{ht}^{nput}$
\end_inset

 being the effective input.
 In the second case, one can simply define production as an homogenous function
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta:Y_{t}=Q_{t}^{\theta}$
\end_inset

 In case of a technology with increasing (resp.
 decreasing) return-to-scale, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta>1$
\end_inset

 (resp.
 
\begin_inset Formula $<1$
\end_inset

 ).
 Integrating technical progress and non constant return-to-scale leads to
 the following input demand: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
I_{ht}^{nput}=\theta^{-1}y_{t}-p_{ht}^{rog}-\sum_{h=1,h\neq h'}^{H}\eta_{hh'}\varphi_{h't}(p_{ht}^{X}-p_{h't}^{X})\label{eq:Input demand}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming constant return to scale, this log-linear specification has been
 recently estimated for the Euro area by Lemoine et al.
 (2010) using the Kalman filter to extract the trend of technical progress.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
B-2
\begin_inset space \quad{}
\end_inset

GCES consumer utility function and demand for goods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Three-ME, the demand for goods is treated in a similar way as the demand
 for input.
 Let us assume that at a first stage the consumer divides (eventually via
 an intertemporal maximization program) her revenue between expenditures
 and savings.
 For a given level desired volume of expenditure 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 , the consumer is then assumed to minimize the cost of this expenditure.
 The substitutability between the different consumption goods (or expenditures),
 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{h}$
\end_inset

 , is measured through a 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 goods-utility function having the same property as the production function
 defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: production function"

\end_inset

.
 Formally the optimization program is the same as the one of the producer.
 It consists in minimizing the cost of expenditure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Cost function"

\end_inset

 subject to the utility function constraint 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: production function"

\end_inset

.
 The demand for goods is thus 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:demand of factors"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that minimizing the cost of expenditure subject to a utility function
 constraint give the same result as the standard approach which consists
 in maximizing the utility 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: production function"

\end_inset

 subject to a budget constraint 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:budget constraint"

\end_inset

: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{h=1}^{H}P_{ht}^{X}X_{ht}=P_{t}^{Q}Q_{t}\label{eq:budget constraint}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Lagrangian to this problem is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L_{t}=Q_{t}-\lambda\bigg(\sum_{h=1}^{H}P_{ht}^{X}X_{ht}-P_{t}^{Q}Q_{t}\bigg)\label{Lagrangian}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The necessary first order conditions (
\begin_inset Formula $L'(X_{ht})=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L'(\lambda)=0)$
\end_inset

 are the well-know conditions that the ratio between marginal utilities
 of two goods equals the one between their prices (Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FOC"

\end_inset

 and thus
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:input share"

\end_inset

) and the budget constraint (Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:budget constraint"

\end_inset

).
 Using a first-order Taylor expansion on Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:budget constraint"

\end_inset

 (divided by
\begin_inset Formula $P^{Q}$
\end_inset

) in the neighbourhood of the stationary equilibrium characterized by the
 stability of price ratios ( 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{h}^{X}/P_{h'}^{X}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $P_{h}^{X}/P^{Q}$
\end_inset

 ), allows for rewriting the budget constraint as
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Prod function bis"

\end_inset

.
 As we have now the same system to solve as in the producer case (Equations
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:input share"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Prod function bis"

\end_inset

), the demand for good is thus 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:demand of factors"

\end_inset

.
 Notice that the particular case of a CES function 
\begin_inset Formula $(\eta_{hh'}/P_{h'}^{X})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:demand of factors"

\end_inset

 simplifies.
 To see this, let us first use a first-order Taylor expansion on Equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:budget constraint"

\end_inset

 (divided by 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{t}$
\end_inset

) in the neighbourhood of the stationary equilibrium characterized by the
 stability of ratios between volumes 
\begin_inset Formula $(X_{h}/X_{h'}X_{h}/Q)$
\end_inset

,.
 This conveniently allows expressing the consumer price as a weighted average
 of the prices of goods, the weight being the share into consumption (Equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:value share"

\end_inset

): 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
\dot{P_{t}^{Q}} & =\sum_{h=1}^{H}\varphi_{ht}\dot{P}_{ht}^{X}\Leftrightarrow p_{t}^{Q}=\sum_{h=1}^{H}\varphi_{ht}p_{ht}^{X}\label{eq:Consumer price function}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming a constant elasticity of substitution 
\begin_inset Formula $(\eta_{hh'}=\eta)$
\end_inset

 between goods and combining the price equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Consumer price function"

\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:demand of factors"

\end_inset

, the demand for goods simplifies and depends only on the relative price
 between the price of goods and the consumer price:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x_{t}=q_{t}-\eta(p_{ht}^{X}-p_{t}^{Q})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Not surprisingly this relation is the same as the one deduced from a direct
 maximization of CES utility function subject to a budget constraint (see
 Blanchard and Fischer, 1989; Blanchard and Kiyotaki, 1987; Dixit and Stiglitz,
 1977).
 The only difference is that the consumer price index
\begin_inset Formula $(P_{t}^{Q})$
\end_inset

 is a linear approximation of the Dixit-Stiglitz index which is a CES function
 of the price of goods.
 As demonstrated by Arrow et al.
 (1961), Leontief and Cobb-Douglas functions are particular cases of a CES
 function where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 tends to 0 and 1 respectively.
\end_layout

